00:06:12.390 --> 00:06:16.440
Early money-- remember some
of our walk down memory lane.

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:22.620
Some of these early monies
fell apart, became extinct,

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:24.428
when they got debased.

00:06:24.428 --> 00:06:26.220
And we talked about,
early in the semester,

00:06:26.220 --> 00:06:27.900
even the story about it.

00:06:27.900 --> 00:06:30.990
It was, I think, a British--

00:06:30.990 --> 00:06:33.960
when the British got
to the island of Yap,

00:06:33.960 --> 00:06:36.900
they went off a couple miles
and quarried the stones

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:39.450
and kept bringing
more yap stones there.

00:06:39.450 --> 00:06:42.240
And all of a sudden,
it got debased.

00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:45.710
And then, of course, money
turned to paper money.

00:06:45.710 --> 00:06:47.950
And in the bottom
left-hand corner,

00:06:47.950 --> 00:06:50.730
it started as
warehouse receipts.

00:06:50.730 --> 00:06:53.040
So the paper was
just a representation

00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:54.630
of the store of value--

00:06:54.630 --> 00:06:59.310
the metal, or the corn, or
the wheat that we had earlier.

00:06:59.310 --> 00:07:02.460
Another important
thing was ledgers.

00:07:02.460 --> 00:07:04.930
Who wants to remind the
class what a ledger is?

00:07:04.930 --> 00:07:08.510
Why do ledgers matter?

00:07:08.510 --> 00:07:10.310
Anybody want to-- ledgers?

00:07:10.310 --> 00:07:13.865
All right, clearly I
didn't make it on ledgers.

00:07:16.790 --> 00:07:18.605
Hugo?

00:07:18.605 --> 00:07:21.780
AUDIENCE: It's transaction
history, basically.

00:07:21.780 --> 00:07:23.630
GARY GENSLER: A store
transaction history.

00:07:23.630 --> 00:07:26.620
What else is there?

00:07:26.620 --> 00:07:27.460
AUDIENCE: Balances.

00:07:27.460 --> 00:07:29.312
GARY GENSLER: Balances of?

00:07:29.312 --> 00:07:30.640
AUDIENCE: Accounts.

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:31.810
GARY GENSLER: Accounts.

00:07:31.810 --> 00:07:34.420
So it stores a balance
and a transaction.

00:07:34.420 --> 00:07:37.980
So you can think of it
as a flow and a balance.

00:07:37.980 --> 00:07:40.510
The flow is the transaction--

00:07:40.510 --> 00:07:43.380
I give Hugo money.

00:07:43.380 --> 00:07:46.470
Regardless of who gives Hugo
money, here's his balance.

00:07:46.470 --> 00:07:49.410
So an income statement
and a balance sheet

00:07:49.410 --> 00:07:51.210
is a flow and a balance.

00:07:51.210 --> 00:07:57.440
But ledgers and keeping ledgers
go back thousands of years.

00:07:57.440 --> 00:08:00.550
So blockchain technology
is really about money,

00:08:00.550 --> 00:08:02.860
but it's also about a
database that has ledgers.

00:08:02.860 --> 00:08:04.750
And ledgers usually
store things of value.

