00:08:39.960 --> 00:08:41.335
[INAUDIBLE] there
are things that

00:08:41.335 --> 00:08:45.466
are important in fiat
currency, or is helpful.

00:08:45.466 --> 00:08:50.440
Fiat currency is important
for paying taxes.

00:08:50.440 --> 00:08:56.230
And it is allegedly backed
by the social understanding

00:08:56.230 --> 00:09:00.707
that the central bank will
respect those notes at the end.

00:09:00.707 --> 00:09:01.540
GARY GENSLER: Right.

00:09:01.540 --> 00:09:03.850
So it's actually--
you're on to this.

00:09:03.850 --> 00:09:06.130
It's accepted for taxes.

00:09:06.130 --> 00:09:07.330
It's legal tender.

00:09:07.330 --> 00:09:09.283
So actually, society
gets together,

00:09:09.283 --> 00:09:11.200
through its parliament,
through its executive,

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:13.740
and passes a law that
says it's legal tender.

00:09:13.740 --> 00:09:15.280
That gives it a huge leg up.

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:17.440
But this is what
it's really about.

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:19.900
It has huge network effects.

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:21.890
And I wrote this in
the CoinDesk article.

00:09:21.890 --> 00:09:26.440
The question I have
for any new currency

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:28.780
is, how does it compete with
those incredible network

00:09:28.780 --> 00:09:30.250
effects?

00:09:30.250 --> 00:09:33.400
And we talk about Facebook
has incredible network effects

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:34.510
because--

00:09:34.510 --> 00:09:36.400
two billion members.

00:09:36.400 --> 00:09:39.880
But even money, as a
technology, has a network effect

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:43.090
because people readily accept
it as a unit of account,

00:09:43.090 --> 00:09:47.480
a medium of exchange,
a store of value.

00:09:47.480 --> 00:09:51.200
And it only loses that
network effect, usually,

00:09:51.200 --> 00:09:54.050
when it gets
debased, when people

00:09:54.050 --> 00:09:56.840
can't be confident that
it's a good store of value

00:09:56.840 --> 00:09:59.240
because somebody else
can mint a lot of it,

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:06.170
or print a lot of it, or a king
starts to print too much of it.

00:10:06.170 --> 00:10:09.380
But it has an extraordinary
network effect.

00:10:09.380 --> 00:10:11.030
On the other hand,
sometimes currencies

00:10:11.030 --> 00:10:13.850
are a little bit challenged,
like the euro right now.

00:10:13.850 --> 00:10:15.930
Will the euro ultimately work?

00:10:15.930 --> 00:10:18.230
That's for a different class
and a different lecture,

00:10:18.230 --> 00:10:21.650
but will the euro
ultimately work long term?

00:10:21.650 --> 00:10:26.300
I have my doubts whether it
will work for decades to come,

00:10:26.300 --> 00:10:29.620
because there's so
many jurisdictions.

00:10:29.620 --> 00:10:32.230
And there's not a
unified fiscal account,

00:10:32.230 --> 00:10:40.790
not a unified economy, and not
truly free movement of labor

00:10:40.790 --> 00:10:44.850
across that continent.

00:10:44.850 --> 00:10:46.590
So that's fiat currency.

00:10:46.590 --> 00:10:50.970
It's sort of the game in town
that then Satoshi Nakamoto

00:10:50.970 --> 00:10:53.070
is was addressing.

00:10:53.070 --> 00:10:55.900
And you all read the
eight-page paper,

00:10:55.900 --> 00:10:57.540
but that was the first line.

00:10:57.540 --> 00:10:59.218
"Been working on a
new electronic cash

00:10:59.218 --> 00:11:01.260
system that's fully
peer-to-peer, with no trusted

00:11:01.260 --> 00:11:02.280
third party."

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:04.470
Basically, as Jihee
said, no central bank.

00:11:04.470 --> 00:11:06.450
Forget about that central bank.

00:11:06.450 --> 00:11:12.000
That was the core
inspiration that was there.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.180
But interestingly, it
wasn't the first try.

00:11:15.180 --> 00:11:17.160
And we talked early
in the semester

00:11:17.160 --> 00:11:20.730
