These slides are on Canvas.

00:12:22.910 --> 00:12:26.350
Download this one slide,
you're the expert.

00:12:26.350 --> 00:12:28.745
Neha Nerula actually
created this slide,

00:12:28.745 --> 00:12:32.060
and I've been using it a lot.

00:12:32.060 --> 00:12:35.420
But anybody remember who
invented this whole concept

00:12:35.420 --> 00:12:36.550
of blocks of data?

00:12:39.970 --> 00:12:40.470
James?

00:12:40.470 --> 00:12:41.640
AUDIENCE: Adam someone?

00:12:41.640 --> 00:12:42.140
Back?

00:12:42.140 --> 00:12:43.765
GARY GENSLER: Adam
Back is a good name,

00:12:43.765 --> 00:12:46.140
but he's not the guy
that invented this.

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:49.972
He invented something else,
which was proof-of-work.

00:12:52.690 --> 00:12:54.600
Timestamp append-only
logs-- what's

00:12:54.600 --> 00:12:57.840
the longest running
