00:12:57.840 --> 00:12:59.100
AUDIENCE: New York Times?

00:12:59.100 --> 00:12:59.655
GARY GENSLER: New York Times.

00:12:59.655 --> 00:13:00.600
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:13:00.600 --> 00:13:01.433
AUDIENCE: Crossword.

00:13:01.433 --> 00:13:05.700
GARY GENSLER: All
right, here he is.

00:13:05.700 --> 00:13:10.480
So two Bell Labs scientists--
this is one of them.

00:13:10.480 --> 00:13:14.560
Two Bell Labs scientists
came up with this concept

00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:19.000
that you could take a bunch
of data, put it through what's

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:23.320
called a cryptographic
hash function,

00:13:23.320 --> 00:13:24.637
and that's a commitment scheme.

00:13:24.637 --> 00:13:26.970
You couldn't change it, because
if you changed anything,

00:13:26.970 --> 00:13:30.360
the hash function would change.

00:13:30.360 --> 00:13:32.430
So what's a cryptographic
hash function?

00:13:32.430 --> 00:13:34.350
That's when I use
this idea of you

00:13:34.350 --> 00:13:37.080
can take the entire
library of Congress,

00:13:37.080 --> 00:13:39.780
and put it into a little
thing called a hash function,

00:13:39.780 --> 00:13:45.150
and end up with a
string of characters,

00:13:45.150 --> 00:13:52.280
a hexadecimal output.

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:59.790
But a hash function is the key
to what this guy figured out.

00:13:59.790 --> 00:14:02.660
And, of course, this.

00:14:02.660 --> 00:14:04.370
That's the key.

00:14:04.370 --> 00:14:06.890
There was only two
bits of cryptography

00:14:06.890 --> 00:14:08.660
in this whole class.

00:14:08.660 --> 00:14:12.710
And I know that it seemed like,
oh, why are we teaching this?

00:14:12.710 --> 00:14:15.870
But it's this idea that you
can take a whole bunch of data,

00:14:15.870 --> 00:14:17.810
put it into this thing
called a hash function,

00:14:17.810 --> 00:14:19.340
and it commits to it.

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:22.520
Because if you change
any piece of the data--

00:14:22.520 --> 00:14:24.700
any individual
piece-- you're going

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:28.380
to get a different output.

00:14:28.380 --> 00:14:32.928
And so it's really the key to
it is that it commits something.

00:14:32.928 --> 00:14:35.220
You can do it with the New
York Times crossword puzzle,

00:14:35.220 --> 00:14:41.490
and that was just my
observation on it.

00:14:41.490 --> 00:14:43.380
So it's about data commitment.

00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:46.860
The other thing that
Satoshi Nakamoto used

00:14:46.860 --> 00:14:51.750
was asymmetric cryptography,
or digital signatures.

00:14:51.750 --> 00:14:54.660
I pulled one of the graphics
that we talked about.

00:14:54.660 --> 00:14:59.850
But the idea being that,
long ago, cryptography

00:14:59.850 --> 00:15:01.980
was, how do I encrypt
something because I'm

00:15:01.980 --> 00:15:04.910
in a military campaign?

00:15:04.910 --> 00:15:07.520
And I would, maybe,
just transpose.

00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:10.550
The simplest cryptography
from thousands of years

00:15:10.550 --> 00:15:13.550
ago was transposing
every letter.

00:15:13.550 --> 00:15:16.130
An A becomes a B,
a B becomes a C.

00:15:16.130 --> 00:15:18.740
That would be a
transposition of one.

00:15:18.740 --> 00:15:23.640
Well, that's pretty hard to
imagine that anybody got away

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:24.140
with that.

00:15:24.140 --> 00:15:26.990
But that was early cryptography,
thousands of years ago-- just

00:15:26.990 --> 00:15:29.780
simple transposition.

00:15:29.780 --> 00:15:32.330
By the mid-20th
century, there was

00:15:32.330 --> 00:15:35.150
very complex
transpositions, which

00:15:35.150 --> 00:15:38.240
were called keys and enigma.

00:15:38.240 --> 00:15:41.900
If you ever go back and watch
that movie Imitation Games,

00:15:41.900 --> 00:15:45.110
there was five metal rotors--

00:15:45.110 --> 00:15:46.910
they were electronic rotors--

00:15:46.910 --> 00:15:48.160
that changed.

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:54.110
And every day, the Germans
would change the five rotors.

00:15:54.110 --> 00:15:56.900
But still, they were
symmetric cryptography.

00:15:56.900 --> 00:16:02.900
The U boats actually
had the same five rotors

00:16:02.900 --> 00:16:06.440
as high command out of--

00:16:06.440 --> 00:16:09.070
Berlin, let's say.

00:16:09.070 --> 00:16:11.510
So somebody came
along in the 1970s

00:16:11.510 --> 00:16:13.220
and said, what if
the key is different?

00:16:13.220 --> 00:16:14.210
It's asymmetric.

00:16:14.210 --> 00:16:16.140
There's a private
key, and a public key.

00:16:16.140 --> 00:16:21.550
The public key, everybody gets,
but the private key, you keep.

00:16:21.550 --> 00:16:23.800
And some of those
computer sites--

00:16:23.800 --> 00:16:26.680
cryptographers-- are
here, right here, at MIT.

00:16:26.680 --> 00:16:30.730
Ron Rivest teaches a
course in cryptography.

00:16:30.730 --> 00:16:34.440
But that invention, in
the 1970s, is really key.

00:16:34.440 --> 00:16:36.520
So it's hash functions,
and this concept

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:39.110
of a private key
and a public key,

00:16:39.110 --> 00:16:42.500
and of course a digital
signature that goes with it.

00:16:42.500 --> 00:16:46.040
You probably don't even need to
remember much about this class

00:16:46.040 --> 00:16:46.557
about this.

00:16:46.557 --> 00:16:48.140
But just know there's
something called

00:16:48.140 --> 00:16:50.810
a private key and a public key.

00:16:50.810 --> 00:16:54.740
And then, Nakamoto's
real innovation

00:16:54.740 --> 00:16:56.480
was off of Adam Back.

00:16:56.480 --> 00:17:01.340
And Adam Back said, if I use
some computational work--

00:17:01.340 --> 00:17:05.210
if I use computational work
to find a hash function that

00:17:05.210 --> 00:17:08.930
has a predetermined
number of zeros,

00:17:08.930 --> 00:17:10.310
it's not much of a puzzle.

00:17:10.310 --> 00:17:12.380
It's a random number generation.

00:17:12.380 --> 00:17:16.099
People will say proof-of-work
is a computational puzzle.

00:17:16.099 --> 00:17:19.150
It is simply running--

00:17:19.150 --> 00:17:21.770
this thing called mining
is running-- electricity

00:17:21.770 --> 00:17:24.454
until you get the right
number of leading zeros.

00:17:27.140 --> 00:17:29.270
But it can be
efficiently verified.

00:17:29.270 --> 00:17:32.810
So the characteristics of
proof-of-work is of work is--

00:17:32.810 --> 00:17:34.760
invented in 1997.

00:17:34.760 --> 00:17:38.360
Blockchains were
invented in 1991.

00:17:38.360 --> 00:17:40.700
But what Satoshi Nakamoto--

00:17:40.700 --> 00:17:45.500
what she did was she pulled that
together after like 20 or 30

00:17:45.500 --> 00:17:50.180
failed attempts to have a
digital, non-central money

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:53.930
and said, that that's where
blockchain inspiration is.

00:17:56.470 --> 00:17:59.200
And so proof of work--

00:17:59.200 --> 00:18:00.650
I use this little visual.

00:18:00.650 --> 00:18:06.430
But each block-- do you
remember what the word nonce is?

00:18:06.430 --> 00:18:07.760
What's a nonce?

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:10.350
Ross?

00:18:10.350 --> 00:18:13.000
Make me proud, somebody.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:13.665
Can't remember.

00:18:13.665 --> 00:18:14.467
AUDIENCE: And once.

00:18:14.467 --> 00:18:15.550
GARY GENSLER: What's that?

00:18:15.550 --> 00:18:16.930
AUDIENCE: And once.

00:18:16.930 --> 00:18:18.865
GARY GENSLER: And
once-- a number once.

00:18:18.865 --> 00:18:19.990
AUDIENCE: Number used once.

00:18:19.990 --> 00:18:20.668
AUDIENCE: Once.

00:18:20.668 --> 00:18:21.960
GARY GENSLER: Number used once.

00:18:24.490 --> 00:18:28.070
And so why is a nonce
important for proof of work?

00:18:28.070 --> 00:18:29.800
AUDIENCE: Because
it's a unique number.

00:18:29.800 --> 00:18:31.450
GARY GENSLER: It's
a unique number.

00:18:31.450 --> 00:18:34.810
AUDIENCE: And so
establishing the integrity

00:18:34.810 --> 00:18:35.920
of that [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:35.920 --> 00:18:38.200
GARY GENSLER: So all this
whole proof of work--

00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:40.930
I'm just going back as a review,
but the whole proof of work

00:18:40.930 --> 00:18:43.930
is your computer is
going to randomly keep

00:18:43.930 --> 00:18:47.080
picking one thing that changes.

00:18:47.080 --> 00:18:49.630
All the data, all the
transactions are the same,

00:18:49.630 --> 00:18:53.730
but keep changing this
thing called a nonce

00:18:53.730 --> 00:18:58.320
until I get some
leading number of zeros.

00:18:58.320 --> 00:19:01.740
And the whole Bitcoin
network around the globe--

00:19:01.740 --> 00:19:04.860
all it's really doing is running
a random number generation,

00:19:04.860 --> 00:19:09.180
or nonces, until
the hash function

00:19:09.180 --> 00:19:13.600
is solved to have 18
leading zeros right now.

00:19:13.600 --> 00:19:14.950
Or I should say--

00:19:14.950 --> 00:19:20.668
18 leading zeros when Bitcoin's
value was $6,500 a Bitcoin.

00:19:20.668 --> 00:19:22.210
It wouldn't surprise
me if it's going

00:19:22.210 --> 00:19:26.190
to fall down to 17 leading
zeros, or 16 leading zeros,

00:19:26.190 --> 00:19:28.860
because that would
make it easier to find.

00:19:31.770 --> 00:19:36.690
All of that cryptography is just
to make the database structure.

00:19:36.690 --> 00:19:42.290
This database structure
that is in blockchain--

00:19:42.290 --> 00:19:43.560
to make this work.

00:19:43.560 --> 00:19:46.860
All that cryptography of hash
functions, digital signatures,

00:19:46.860 --> 00:19:49.440
and a little proof
of work is to make it

00:19:49.440 --> 00:19:53.010
what's called nearly immutable.

00:19:53.010 --> 00:19:55.590
And I'm putting the word
"nearly" in because nothing's

00:19:55.590 --> 00:19:56.590
truly immutable.

00:19:56.590 --> 00:20:00.770
You could overwhelm even
the Bitcoin network.

00:20:00.770 --> 00:20:04.745
Questions about the technology?

00:20:04.745 --> 00:20:05.430
[INAUDIBLE]

00:20:05.430 --> 00:20:07.930
AUDIENCE: Could you just go
over the number of leading zeros

00:20:07.930 --> 00:20:09.510
concept again?

00:20:09.510 --> 00:20:15.800
GARY GENSLER: So the concept
behind the proof of work

00:20:15.800 --> 00:20:25.560
that Adam Back came up with
in the late 1990s was--

00:20:25.560 --> 00:20:30.780
gotta run some data
through a hash function.

00:20:30.780 --> 00:20:34.020
In his case, in Adam
Back's case, it was emails.

00:20:34.020 --> 00:20:39.030
Literally run an email all the
way through a hash function,

00:20:39.030 --> 00:20:42.810
and then add an additional
bit of data to it--

00:20:42.810 --> 00:20:46.930
this nonce, a number
that's used once--

00:20:46.930 --> 00:20:51.890
and run that nonce randomly
until the hash that comes out.

00:20:51.890 --> 00:20:53.700
And my little
visual at the bottom

00:20:53.700 --> 00:20:56.790
there has some
leading zeros to it.

00:20:59.860 --> 00:21:01.360
AUDIENCE: So
beginning of the hash

00:21:01.360 --> 00:21:03.610
will be its number of zeros?

00:21:03.610 --> 00:21:04.360
GARY GENSLER: Yes.

00:21:04.360 --> 00:21:07.350
So in this case,
four leading zeros--

00:21:07.350 --> 00:21:09.790
in that little visual there.

00:21:09.790 --> 00:21:12.280
All the data that
goes into a block--

00:21:12.280 --> 00:21:16.960
in Bitcoin, 1,000 to 1,500
transactions all go in.

00:21:16.960 --> 00:21:19.360
They're rolled up in this
thing called a Merkle tree,

00:21:19.360 --> 00:21:21.700
but it all goes in.

00:21:21.700 --> 00:21:23.440
And the only thing
that's changing

00:21:23.440 --> 00:21:28.580
is the miners are trying
to find a random nonce

00:21:28.580 --> 00:21:33.810
until the hash has certain
number of leading zeros.

00:21:33.810 --> 00:21:38.580
When Nakamoto wrote the paper,
the difficulty was, I think,

00:21:38.580 --> 00:21:40.630
10 leading zeros.

00:21:40.630 --> 00:21:43.815
And you could solve
that on a laptop.

00:21:47.360 --> 00:21:50.280
With eight more leading zeros--

00:21:50.280 --> 00:21:52.320
and since it's hexadecimal--

00:21:52.320 --> 00:21:56.700
I guess it's 16 to
the eighth power

00:21:56.700 --> 00:22:04.477
harder, or something like
seven trillion times harder.

00:22:04.477 --> 00:22:05.060
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:22:10.460 --> 00:22:12.580
AUDIENCE: Let's assume
that you and I were trying

00:22:12.580 --> 00:22:14.640
to have a transaction today.

00:22:14.640 --> 00:22:18.849
And I'm going to
keep some coins.

00:22:18.849 --> 00:22:22.060
And I'm [INAUDIBLE]
these for everyone

00:22:22.060 --> 00:22:24.120
who's transacting
many, many times

00:22:24.120 --> 00:22:30.370
and adding layers of difficulty
to the transaction that we had.

00:22:30.370 --> 00:22:35.210
If I want to use my
balance in five years,

00:22:35.210 --> 00:22:37.800
how do we know
what my balance is?

00:22:37.800 --> 00:22:41.000
I need to go back
through all the history

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:42.250
to know that I have a balance?

00:22:42.250 --> 00:22:47.350
GARY GENSLER: So at the heart
of the blockchain technology,

00:22:47.350 --> 00:22:50.410
the Bitcoin network, but
also all the other networks,

00:22:50.410 --> 00:22:54.130
is the entire transaction
history is public.

00:22:54.130 --> 00:22:56.230
This both gives us its
strength, but it's also

00:22:56.230 --> 00:22:58.870
one of its challenges.

00:22:58.870 --> 00:23:02.470
And so, yes, even
five years from now,

00:23:02.470 --> 00:23:08.300
if you want to use
one of your Bitcoins--

00:23:08.300 --> 00:23:11.680
which are stored
on the blockchain--

00:23:11.680 --> 00:23:14.890
you have to be able to show
that here is a transaction

00:23:14.890 --> 00:23:16.390
output from five years ago.

00:23:16.390 --> 00:23:21.710
If you remember, there is both
transaction output models--

00:23:21.710 --> 00:23:26.480
Bitcoin is a system that keeps
all the individual transactions

00:23:26.480 --> 00:23:28.780
in a set called the UTXO--

00:23:28.780 --> 00:23:32.920
the Unspent
Transaction Output Set.

00:23:32.920 --> 00:23:37.300
You'd have to be able to show
that you have that in 25 years,

00:23:37.300 --> 00:23:38.050
you said?

00:23:38.050 --> 00:23:44.200
2023-- in 2023, you'd have
to be able to show that.

00:23:44.200 --> 00:23:46.810
AUDIENCE: So it's
also a balance.

00:23:46.810 --> 00:23:51.260
They all spent this balance
in the transaction [INAUDIBLE]

00:23:51.260 --> 00:23:53.060
a record.

00:23:53.060 --> 00:23:55.270
GARY GENSLER: It is
a record of an output

00:23:55.270 --> 00:23:57.830
from an individual transaction.

00:23:57.830 --> 00:24:01.620
So yes, it is like a balance.

00:24:01.620 --> 00:24:07.610
But because Bitcoin does not
add up all of those individual--

00:24:07.610 --> 00:24:12.410
if you had 13
individual outputs,

00:24:12.410 --> 00:24:16.450
the Bitcoin network will
not add up those 13.

00:24:16.450 --> 00:24:21.226
You'd have to use each of those
individually as new inputs.

00:24:21.226 --> 00:24:26.170
AUDIENCE: And that one is
on the last block, as well.

00:24:26.170 --> 00:24:28.627
But I'd have to go
back [INAUDIBLE]..

00:24:28.627 --> 00:24:30.460
GARY GENSLER: All right,
so the question is,

00:24:30.460 --> 00:24:31.600
does the last block--

00:24:31.600 --> 00:24:36.190
Bitcoin has 550-some 1,000
blocks of data right now.

00:24:36.190 --> 00:24:40.040
Does the last block
store all of the data?

00:24:40.040 --> 00:24:45.710
And the answer is, no, but
it does store a hash function

00:24:45.710 --> 00:24:49.160
from the previous block,
which stores a hash function

00:24:49.160 --> 00:24:51.100
from the previous block.

00:24:51.100 --> 00:24:57.450
So your transaction output might
be on block number 420,000,

00:24:57.450 --> 00:25:01.760
130,000 blocks ago.

00:25:01.760 --> 00:25:04.430
But what shows that
it's verifiable

00:25:04.430 --> 00:25:08.480
is that each one of these blocks
are linked to another block

00:25:08.480 --> 00:25:10.460
through this thing called
a commitment scheme

00:25:10.460 --> 00:25:12.790
called a hash function.

00:25:12.790 --> 00:25:17.120
So technically speaking,
the latest block

00:25:17.120 --> 00:25:19.870
has a number in it--

00:25:19.870 --> 00:25:22.750
a hexadecimal number,
but a number in it--

00:25:22.750 --> 00:25:25.660
called a hash function
that is committed to.

00:25:25.660 --> 00:25:28.870
Because all the data
that's come before it--

00:25:28.870 --> 00:25:31.770
all the millions of
transactions before it--

00:25:31.770 --> 00:25:34.060
if somebody even
changes one of them,

00:25:34.060 --> 00:25:37.672
you'll know that
it's been tampered.

00:25:37.672 --> 00:25:41.460
AUDIENCE: Let's say I want
to use that balance I have.

00:25:41.460 --> 00:25:45.500
Where do the blockchain
verify that I have that?

00:25:45.500 --> 00:25:48.180
Is it on the last
block, or does it

00:25:48.180 --> 00:25:53.495
go back as long as it
finds the [INAUDIBLE]??

00:25:53.495 --> 00:25:54.870
GARY GENSLER: In
essence, it does

00:25:54.870 --> 00:25:59.420
both, because the last
block better be valid.

00:25:59.420 --> 00:26:01.450
But for you to
spend something, it

00:26:01.450 --> 00:26:10.180
has to really go back and find
that the input that you now

00:26:10.180 --> 00:26:15.420
want to use is an output
that has not yet been spent.

00:26:15.420 --> 00:26:18.570
Eric, did you have something
that you were trying to--

00:26:18.570 --> 00:26:21.660
AUDIENCE: Yeah, it was
a very nice explanation.

00:26:21.660 --> 00:26:24.780
You have to go all the way
where your transaction-- where

00:26:24.780 --> 00:26:29.365
you got the Bitcoin
was, whatever

00:26:29.365 --> 00:26:32.225
block it is [INAUDIBLE]
through the blockchain.

00:26:32.225 --> 00:26:35.470
If you would try
to get those coins

00:26:35.470 --> 00:26:41.160
and use them as a [INAUDIBLE]
for whatever transaction

00:26:41.160 --> 00:26:44.045
you want to do, you have
to go all the way back.

00:26:44.045 --> 00:26:45.420
GARY GENSLER: And
this complexity

00:26:45.420 --> 00:26:47.310
is part of the
reason why it doesn't

00:26:47.310 --> 00:26:49.110
have the same performance--

00:26:49.110 --> 00:26:53.130
doesn't have the same
scalability-- yet.

00:26:53.130 --> 00:26:56.550
I'm one that believes in a--

00:26:56.550 --> 00:26:59.100
I'm optimistic that some
of these scalability

00:26:59.100 --> 00:27:01.230
and performance issues
will be overcome.

00:27:01.230 --> 00:27:04.050
But it might take three,
five, seven years.

