00:49:54.950 --> 00:49:57.760
And the key thing-- and
if you take anything away

00:49:57.760 --> 00:50:00.460
about exchanges, other than
right now they're unregulated

00:50:00.460 --> 00:50:03.520
and they're probably highly
susceptible to front running

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:06.880
and manipulation, is that
they're a little bit different,

00:50:06.880 --> 00:50:09.130
because they're
not just matching

00:50:09.130 --> 00:50:12.370
agents, which the London Stock
Exchange or the New York Stock

00:50:12.370 --> 00:50:15.430
Exchange are [INAUDIBLE],, but
they also are counterparties

00:50:15.430 --> 00:50:16.510
and custodians.

00:50:19.330 --> 00:50:22.750
The other thing to take
away about crypto exchanges

00:50:22.750 --> 00:50:24.430
is they're highly centralized.

00:50:24.430 --> 00:50:28.330
So it's a central irony that
Satoshi Nakamoto is trying

00:50:28.330 --> 00:50:32.190
to have decentralization,
and yet there's

00:50:32.190 --> 00:50:35.090
an awful lot of centralization.

00:50:35.090 --> 00:50:37.580
So I'm just thinking
about core takeaways.

00:50:37.580 --> 00:50:39.980
If you're ever investing, or
you're thinking about this,

00:50:39.980 --> 00:50:42.560
or you're just involved in
a dinner party conversation,

00:50:42.560 --> 00:50:45.620
that central irony in
a decentralized space,

00:50:45.620 --> 00:50:51.530
95% of the real transactions are
happening on crypto exchanges.

00:50:54.140 --> 00:50:56.130
My thought about
crypto exchanges--

00:50:56.130 --> 00:50:59.990
they'll not be 200 of them
that much longer either.

00:50:59.990 --> 00:51:02.060
We talked about
Initial Coin Offerings.

00:51:02.060 --> 00:51:05.670
Central takeaway is they're
fundraising vehicles.

00:51:05.670 --> 00:51:07.430
Whether you believe
in or not believe

00:51:07.430 --> 00:51:11.420
in the US and Canadian
approach under the Howey Test,

00:51:11.420 --> 00:51:16.760
but they help build a network,
raise money in anticipation

00:51:16.760 --> 00:51:19.985
the tokens are issued
before it's functional.

00:51:19.985 --> 00:51:24.110
I think the latest
study was that--

00:51:24.110 --> 00:51:26.570
what was it-- 1 and 1/2 percent
are actually functional,

00:51:26.570 --> 00:51:29.210
and 98 and 1/2 percent
are issued pre-functional.

00:51:29.210 --> 00:51:31.550
So that's not a problem.

00:51:31.550 --> 00:51:34.610
It's just-- that's the--

00:51:34.610 --> 00:51:36.830
means it's probably an
investment vehicle, not

00:51:36.830 --> 00:51:38.270
a utility token.

00:51:38.270 --> 00:51:40.260
And that whole thing
about utility token

00:51:40.260 --> 00:51:46.010
versus security tokens, it
stretched pretty darn thin.

00:51:46.010 --> 00:51:48.680
We talked about public
policy frameworks,

00:51:48.680 --> 00:51:51.200
guarding against illicit
activity, financial stability,

00:51:51.200 --> 00:51:52.610
investing public.

00:51:52.610 --> 00:51:56.090
My overall thought on this--

00:51:56.090 --> 00:51:59.210
and I accept that others
will have other views--

00:51:59.210 --> 00:52:05.240
is that any new technology, if
it grows to be economy-wide,

00:52:05.240 --> 00:52:08.630
needs to live within
public policy frameworks,

00:52:08.630 --> 00:52:12.560
or society will change those
public policy frameworks

00:52:12.560 --> 00:52:14.190
modestly.

00:52:14.190 --> 00:52:16.070
But you still want
to protect the public

00:52:16.070 --> 00:52:18.790
against core social goods.

00:52:18.790 --> 00:52:20.590
It happened when the
railroad came along.

00:52:20.590 --> 00:52:23.230
It happened when telegram came
along in the 19th century.

00:52:23.230 --> 00:52:25.610
It happened with the internet.

00:52:25.610 --> 00:52:27.770
Societies don't
have technologies

00:52:27.770 --> 00:52:33.870
fully outside of whatever
social fabric we want to create.

00:52:33.870 --> 00:52:35.850
And we do that
social fabric stuff

00:52:35.850 --> 00:52:40.770
through politics and parliaments
and executives and regulators.

00:52:40.770 --> 00:52:45.490
But we don't leave big parts
of our economy outside of it.

00:52:45.490 --> 00:52:47.545
This stuff is still small.

00:52:47.545 --> 00:52:49.240
It's $100 billion.

00:52:49.240 --> 00:52:54.240
The worldwide capital markets
are over $300 trillion.

00:52:54.240 --> 00:52:57.930
But it's gained a lot
of public attention.

00:52:57.930 --> 00:53:01.740
And particularly, we want to
guard against illicit activity.

00:53:01.740 --> 00:53:04.650
Most folks do.

00:53:04.650 --> 00:53:05.790
Maybe not everybody.

00:53:05.790 --> 00:53:07.310
But most do.

00:53:07.310 --> 00:53:08.850
No, I recognize.

00:53:08.850 --> 00:53:09.990
Hopefully, you all do.

00:53:09.990 --> 00:53:10.800
Well, I don't know.

00:53:13.320 --> 00:53:16.790
So we talked about the US
Securities Law, the Howey Test.

00:53:16.790 --> 00:53:21.090
It's not-- if you forget the
Howey Test, it's totally fine.

00:53:21.090 --> 00:53:24.570
But it's core to these
initial coin offerings,

00:53:24.570 --> 00:53:26.490
and it was that four-part test--

00:53:26.490 --> 00:53:28.500
investment of money in
a common enterprise,

00:53:28.500 --> 00:53:31.030
expectation of profits.

00:53:31.030 --> 00:53:32.760
So if you get into
some debate, and you

00:53:32.760 --> 00:53:34.330
want to have some
fun with somebody,

00:53:34.330 --> 00:53:35.850
you can say you
know the Howey Test.

00:53:38.550 --> 00:53:40.390
But it's really more this.

00:53:40.390 --> 00:53:42.450
I prefer the Duck Test.

00:53:42.450 --> 00:53:44.280
Just use common sense.

