Telegram raised $1.7 billion.

00:55:29.420 --> 00:55:31.430
Do they figure out
what to do and make

00:55:31.430 --> 00:55:34.040
a real live effort in 2019?

00:55:34.040 --> 00:55:36.140
And it will test the economics.

00:55:36.140 --> 00:55:38.060
And by the way, Eric,
it might pull me more

00:55:38.060 --> 00:55:40.640
towards where you are, right?

00:55:40.640 --> 00:55:43.610
I mean Telegram's-- they got a
lot of smart folks over there

00:55:43.610 --> 00:55:45.320
working on this.

00:55:45.320 --> 00:55:47.820
And by the way, Facebook
has advertisements out

00:55:47.820 --> 00:55:50.380
hiring people on
blockchain technology.

00:55:50.380 --> 00:55:53.280
So there's a lot of very
big tech companies hiring

00:55:53.280 --> 00:55:55.060
and recruiting in this space.

00:55:55.060 --> 00:55:57.930
But I think 2019 will be
interesting to see, what does--

00:55:57.930 --> 00:55:58.680
what is Telegram?

00:55:58.680 --> 00:55:59.580
What is Filecoin?

00:55:59.580 --> 00:56:03.000
What do some of the big,
hopefully, well-meaning

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:06.990
companies do with these tokens?

00:56:06.990 --> 00:56:10.650
Central banks-- mostly
in the monitor phase.

00:56:10.650 --> 00:56:12.948
But I'd say the thing
to watch is Sweden.

00:56:12.948 --> 00:56:14.490
It'll be really
interesting what they

00:56:14.490 --> 00:56:16.370
do with their E-krona project.

00:56:16.370 --> 00:56:20.610
Do they go live and say,
inspired by blockchain?

00:56:20.610 --> 00:56:23.490
The E-krona project is
not blockchain technology,

00:56:23.490 --> 00:56:27.930
but it's completely inspired by
Satoshi Nakamoto saying, well,

00:56:27.930 --> 00:56:33.000
we, the central bank, Jihee's
the central bank says,

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:36.240
we're going to do what
Satoshi Nakamoto's--

00:56:36.240 --> 00:56:39.630
we're going to have a
central bank digital token.

00:56:39.630 --> 00:56:41.140
You can use it at Starbucks.

00:56:41.140 --> 00:56:42.630
You can use it wherever.

00:56:42.630 --> 00:56:43.410
I'd watch that.

00:56:43.410 --> 00:56:47.690
I think Venezuela will
probably fail on the other end.

00:56:47.690 --> 00:56:48.780
But it'll be interesting.

00:56:48.780 --> 00:56:54.720
There might be some distressed
country that does something.

00:56:54.720 --> 00:56:57.310
So how would I conclude?

00:56:57.310 --> 00:56:58.680
I think blockchain does--

00:56:58.680 --> 00:57:01.110
this is my disclosure.

00:57:01.110 --> 00:57:04.560
I think it does provide a
real peer-to-peer alternative.

00:57:04.560 --> 00:57:08.640
I think it's a legit
live application.

00:57:08.640 --> 00:57:11.860
It might not be the best, but
is it better than some others?

00:57:11.860 --> 00:57:14.550
Is it something you could use?

00:57:14.550 --> 00:57:16.676
Verification and
networking cost--

00:57:16.676 --> 00:57:19.110
I'm going to repeat on that--

00:57:19.110 --> 00:57:21.330
is the key.

00:57:21.330 --> 00:57:23.520
But you always, I think,
have to assess, is it

00:57:23.520 --> 00:57:24.930
the right use case?

00:57:24.930 --> 00:57:28.013
Is this use case
the right use case?

00:57:28.013 --> 00:57:29.430
But as we've talked,
I think there

00:57:29.430 --> 00:57:32.940
are real use cases
more in permissioned

00:57:32.940 --> 00:57:34.510
than permissionless.

00:57:37.270 --> 00:57:38.110
Remember anything.

00:57:38.110 --> 00:57:42.790
Money is just-- we all
humans, the 7 billion

00:57:42.790 --> 00:57:45.730
of us that live now,
have to thank somebody

00:57:45.730 --> 00:57:50.020
about 10,000 years ago, but came
up with this technology called

00:57:50.020 --> 00:57:51.370
money.

00:57:51.370 --> 00:57:53.560
Store value, medium
of exchange, unit

00:57:53.560 --> 00:57:55.870
of account-- it's just a
social construct, which

00:57:55.870 --> 00:57:58.480
is a reason why I say, we
could have a social construct

00:57:58.480 --> 00:58:01.380
that is decentralized money.

00:58:01.380 --> 00:58:04.330
I absolutely believe
we could have that.

00:58:04.330 --> 00:58:06.130
But we'd all have to accept it.

00:58:06.130 --> 00:58:09.160
Where I have less
optimism is that you'd

00:58:09.160 --> 00:58:13.360
want to accept it for a
closed, bounded ecosystem

00:58:13.360 --> 00:58:15.340
only for file storage.

00:58:15.340 --> 00:58:18.430
That's where I'm a
little challenged as to,

00:58:18.430 --> 00:58:23.930
what is the real
economics of that?

00:58:23.930 --> 00:58:25.820
Financial sector's
characteristics

00:58:25.820 --> 00:58:27.560
and challenges--

00:58:27.560 --> 00:58:29.080
is it good?

00:58:29.080 --> 00:58:33.530
It's fertile ground, because
finance is built on ledgers.

00:58:33.530 --> 00:58:35.090
And finance is big--

00:58:35.090 --> 00:58:38.440
7 and 1/2 percent
of our economy.

00:58:38.440 --> 00:58:41.210
And around the globe,
it's anywhere from 5%

00:58:41.210 --> 00:58:43.420
to probably 8% of
those economies.

00:58:43.420 --> 00:58:45.510
Most other countries,
it's less than the US,

00:58:45.510 --> 00:58:49.190
but it's still-- it's big.

00:58:49.190 --> 00:58:50.690
Incumbents are,
of course, looking

00:58:50.690 --> 00:58:52.970
at permissioned blockchains.

00:58:52.970 --> 00:58:54.740
And unfortunately,
crypto finance

00:58:54.740 --> 00:58:57.800
has a bunch of scams and frauds.

00:58:57.800 --> 00:59:01.860
And that hurts the development.

00:59:01.860 --> 00:59:05.730
But I think adoption
will come, but it

00:59:05.730 --> 00:59:08.070
rests on solving a bunch
of technical issues,

00:59:08.070 --> 00:59:11.800
like the Digital Currency
Initiative's trying to solve.

00:59:11.800 --> 00:59:14.560
What are the commercial use
cases and the public policy?

00:59:14.560 --> 00:59:16.110
I wouldn't lead
with public policy.

00:59:16.110 --> 00:59:18.380
I don't think that's
the main issue here.

00:59:18.380 --> 00:59:21.200
But if this is ever
going to be anything,

00:59:21.200 --> 00:59:24.400
it's got to get over that.

00:59:24.400 --> 00:59:26.920
So mostly, it's probably going
to be a catalyst for change,

00:59:26.920 --> 00:59:31.710
more than actual real thoughts.

00:59:31.710 --> 00:59:32.722
Questions?

00:59:35.820 --> 00:59:37.620
Thoughts?

00:59:37.620 --> 00:59:38.185
Eric.

00:59:38.185 --> 00:59:41.653
AUDIENCE: On the
third point, I--

00:59:41.653 --> 00:59:43.320
GARY GENSLER: Use
cases must address why

00:59:43.320 --> 00:59:45.060
versus a traditional database.

00:59:45.060 --> 00:59:46.530
AUDIENCE: I always
had the feeling

00:59:46.530 --> 00:59:49.470
that it seemed the
permissioned space, where

00:59:49.470 --> 00:59:54.190
you have the most or the
biggest urge to prove where--

00:59:54.190 --> 01:00:00.630
if your submission needs a
blockchain solution as opposed

01:00:00.630 --> 01:00:01.925
to a traditional--

01:00:01.925 --> 01:00:05.040
I mean making a case against
the centralized database

01:00:05.040 --> 01:00:08.755
is kind of easy, versus
a distributed database.

01:00:08.755 --> 01:00:11.210
I think it's a little bit tough.

01:00:11.210 --> 01:00:13.987
But in the
permissionless space, I

01:00:13.987 --> 01:00:15.570
think you don't have
to struggle much,

01:00:15.570 --> 01:00:18.810
because it's absolutely
justified that you can--

01:00:18.810 --> 01:00:23.010
because you're dealing with a
decentralized configuration,

01:00:23.010 --> 01:00:27.900
where there's no one in
charge of guaranteeing

01:00:27.900 --> 01:00:30.020
that we have a--

01:00:30.020 --> 01:00:32.310
GARY GENSLER: So Eric's
raising the question,

01:00:32.310 --> 01:00:34.480
why not use a
traditional database?

01:00:34.480 --> 01:00:36.120
Why ever use a permissioned--

01:00:36.120 --> 01:00:37.620
AUDIENCE: In the
permissioned space,

01:00:37.620 --> 01:00:40.080
because permissionless
is perfectly justified.

01:00:40.080 --> 01:00:41.550
But in the
permissioned space, I'm

01:00:41.550 --> 01:00:44.500
not saying it's not justified.

01:00:44.500 --> 01:00:48.840
The point is being
that in our project,

01:00:48.840 --> 01:00:51.810
we argued for a
permissioned system.

01:00:51.810 --> 01:00:53.910
We made some justifications
in that space,

01:00:53.910 --> 01:00:59.970
so the point is that I just
wanted to get your thoughts so

01:00:59.970 --> 01:01:01.760
that in the
permissionless spaces,

01:01:01.760 --> 01:01:04.140
you don't have to
struggle much in that.

01:01:04.140 --> 01:01:08.800
GARY GENSLER: Permissionless
blockchain technology,

01:01:08.800 --> 01:01:10.480
looking forward a
number of years,

01:01:10.480 --> 01:01:13.570
looking forward to when some of
the scalability and performance

01:01:13.570 --> 01:01:17.540
gets better, can give
you verification costs.

01:01:17.540 --> 01:01:22.720
And it's censorship-resistant
or practically

01:01:22.720 --> 01:01:27.010
censorship-resistant, unless
somebody does a 51% attack.

01:01:27.010 --> 01:01:31.120
But so I think that the truly
decentralized distributed

01:01:31.120 --> 01:01:36.480
permissionless system has
a lot of-- a lot to offer.

01:01:36.480 --> 01:01:39.710
But it comes with a lot of
costs, too, and challenges--

01:01:39.710 --> 01:01:44.240
hard to do the governance and
hard to get coordinated action.

01:01:44.240 --> 01:01:46.700
And as you've heard
me say, I think

01:01:46.700 --> 01:01:49.400
there's only probably going
to be a very limited use

01:01:49.400 --> 01:01:56.400
cases for native tokens,
native product-specific tokens

01:01:56.400 --> 01:02:03.690
like a Filecoin or a restaurant
review coin or a health care

01:02:03.690 --> 01:02:04.740
coin.

01:02:04.740 --> 01:02:08.070
I have-- I have my
doubts about that.

01:02:08.070 --> 01:02:11.820
An economy-wide coin, a
cryptocurrency like Bitcoin--

01:02:11.820 --> 01:02:14.190
I think there's more
use, particularly

01:02:14.190 --> 01:02:17.520
if you have a weak central
bank, a weak fiscal policy.

01:02:17.520 --> 01:02:22.620
A country like Venezuela in the
future might adopt something.

01:02:22.620 --> 01:02:24.840
I think there's a lot to
be said for permissionless,

01:02:24.840 --> 01:02:28.590
but permissioned systems versus
traditional databases, I think,

01:02:28.590 --> 01:02:30.180
also gives something.

01:02:30.180 --> 01:02:33.150
And I'll use the Australian
stock exchange for one,

01:02:33.150 --> 01:02:34.950
but they know their customers.

01:02:34.950 --> 01:02:35.910
They know they have--

01:02:35.910 --> 01:02:38.640
I think the number
was 77 members.

01:02:38.640 --> 01:02:42.510
They can take their database
and decentralize it and put it

01:02:42.510 --> 01:02:47.730
on all 77 member companies,
if that's the right number,

01:02:47.730 --> 01:02:51.180
and say, you're
now sharing that.

01:02:51.180 --> 01:02:53.610
And so then there's no
single point of failure,

01:02:53.610 --> 01:02:56.370
and we can lower what's
called reconciliation costs,

01:02:56.370 --> 01:02:59.370
because you all needed
some of that data anyway.

01:02:59.370 --> 01:03:04.620
The historic data-keeping,
the historic nature of it

01:03:04.620 --> 01:03:07.230
came up with each
of those 77 members

01:03:07.230 --> 01:03:09.370
having individual databases.

01:03:09.370 --> 01:03:12.540
So I could see that there is
a real benefit in probably

01:03:12.540 --> 01:03:15.810
efficiency and
lowering costs, which

01:03:15.810 --> 01:03:18.650
means lowering costs
of verification,

01:03:18.650 --> 01:03:20.400
lowering networking
costs, because there's

01:03:20.400 --> 01:03:23.250
77 members, trade finance.

01:03:23.250 --> 01:03:25.030
I could see some
of that as well.

01:03:25.030 --> 01:03:27.240
So that-- but you
might be right.

01:03:27.240 --> 01:03:28.920
Oracle might be
able to just adopt

01:03:28.920 --> 01:03:30.290
that in a traditional database.

01:03:30.290 --> 01:03:30.865
Sabrina.

01:03:30.865 --> 01:03:32.490
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so
it seems like you're

01:03:32.490 --> 01:03:35.800
describing that they have some
form of distributed consensus.

01:03:35.800 --> 01:03:37.390
And that's the
main reason, right?

01:03:37.390 --> 01:03:38.836
But there's--

01:03:38.836 --> 01:03:40.890
GARY GENSLER: And
distributed the data

01:03:40.890 --> 01:03:43.980
stored on multiple nodes,
because it's multiple copies

01:03:43.980 --> 01:03:45.040
of the same data.

01:03:45.040 --> 01:03:47.580
AUDIENCE: Right, but yeah.

01:03:47.580 --> 01:03:50.690
There's-- I mean if that still
can be implemented without

01:03:50.690 --> 01:03:51.770
watching.

